# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diet-in-sikhism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diet-in-sikhism/11th-sikh-regiment] The **11th Sikh Regiment** was an infantry regiment of the British Indian Army.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/11th-sikh-regiment] They could trace their origins to 1922, when after World War I the Indian government reformed the army moving from single battalion regiments to multi battalion regiments.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/11th-sikh-regiment] During World War II a further seven infantry battalions were formed the 6th, 7th, 8th, 9th, 14th, 25th and a machine gun battalion.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/11th-sikh-regiment] The 8th and 9th battalions were converted to Light Anti-Aircraft battalions.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/11th-sikh-regiment] The regiment was allocated to the new Indian Army on independence, becoming the Sikh Regiment.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] The 3HO movement is known for including some practices found in certain Dharmic traditions such as meditation, vegetarianism, and yoga, particularly Kundalini yoga.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] 3HO believes openness to yoga and spiritual ideas are a source of strength.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Both men and women wear turbans and often wear white clothes.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] 3HO requires its members to follow a strict lacto-vegetarian diet.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] The use of alcohol, recreational drugs, and tobacco is forbidden.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Although 3HO claims to practice Sikh teachings and values, the organization is largely condemned by the wider Sikh community, with some going as far as to call it a cult.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] In 1977, Gurucharan Singh Tohra, former President of the Shiromani Gurdwara Parbandhak Committee (SGPC), stated that Harbhajan Singh was not the leader of Sikhism in the Western World as he claimed and denied Singh's claim that the SGPC had given him the title of Siri Singh Sahib.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] In January of 2020, Yogi Bhajan's former secretary Pamela Saharah Dyson (f.k.a.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Premka) published her memoir *Premka: White Bird in a Golden Cage: My Life with Yogi Bhajan*, detailing the intimate non-professional, sexual relationships she and other women had with Harbhajan Singh.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] The release of this memoir prompted allegations of sexual, financial, and emotional abuse on the part of Yogi Bhajan and people close to him.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] These allegations culminated in a civil lawsuit in the city of Los Angeles against Bhajan and members of his circle.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] In response to the allegations 3HO hired *An Olive Branch*, a consultancy specializing in addressing misconduct in spiritual communities, to conduct a third-party investigation.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Dusenbery and Pashaura Singh have concurred that Harbhajan Singh's introduction of Sikh teachings into the West helped identify Sikhism as a world religion while at the same time creating a compelling counter-narrative to that which identified Sikhs solely as a race with a shared history in India.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] I do not care what fantastic interpretations of Kundalini Yoga he gives, the like of which I have never read in any Tantra text, nor known from any living Tantric scholar.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Following the Yogi's death in 2004, a dispute ensued over the governance of those entities and assets.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] In January 2017, the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals determined that the lawsuit was not on its face an ecclesiastical dispute.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] However, in April 2018, Chief Judge Michael Mosman of the U.S.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] District Court for the District of Oregon dismissed the case.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Judge Mosman concluded that there was significant evidence that the 3HO corporate entities were religious in character and thus that the dispute could not be adjudicated in civil court.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Golden Temple of Oregon, a natural foods company that built the Peace Cereal and Yogi Tea brands, was owned by a corporate entity controlled by Yogi Bhajan, and was estimated to be worth around $100,000,000 at the time of his death.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] The company was transferred to Kartar Singh Khalsa for $100, sparking lawsuits over improper disposition of the assets.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Golden Temple's cereal division was sold to Hearthside Food Solutions in May 2010 for $71 million; the executives were later ordered to return more than half of the sale price to a court-appointed receiver.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Golden Temple was renamed East West Tea Company after that sale.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Another SDI-related company, Akal Security, initially hired 3HO members to guard shops and restaurants.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] It grew into a $500 million-a-year company with federal contracts to protect numerous government buildings in Washington, DC and elsewhere, including courthouses, airports, and embassies.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] The founders donated the company to the church in 1980.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] Following the death of Yogi Bhajan, control over Golden Temple and Akal Security was contested in a series of lawsuits in Oregon.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/3ho] In October 2024, HBO premiered the series Breath of Fire, which talks about the mental and sexual abuse of Yogi Bhajan, and 3HO.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Followers of Sikhism do not have a preference for meat or vegetarian consumption.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] There are two views on initiated or "Amritdhari Sikhs" and meat consumption.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] "Amritdhari" Sikhs (i.e. those that follow the Sikh Rehat Maryada - the Official Sikh Code of Conduct) can eat meat (provided it is not Kutha meat).
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] "Amritdharis" that belong to some Sikh sects (e.g.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Akhand Kirtani Jatha, Damdami Taksal, Namdhari) are vehemently against the consumption of meat and eggs.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] The Sikh Gurus have indicated their preference for a simple diet, which could include meat or be vegetarian.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Guru Nanak said that overconsumption of food i.e.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Lobh (Greed) involves a drain on the Earth's resources and thus on life.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] In the case of meat, passages from the Guru Granth Sahib (the holy book of Sikhs, also known as the Adi Granth) say that fools argue over this issue.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] The tenth guru, Guru Gobind Singh, prohibited the Sikhs from the consumption of Kutha (any ritually slaughtered) meat because of the Sikh belief that sacrificing an animal in the name of God is mere ritualism (something to be avoided).
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] In Sikhism, only lacto-vegetarian food is served in the Gurdwara (Sikh temple) but Sikhs are not bound to be meat-free.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] The general consensus is that Sikhs are free to choose whether to adopt a meat diet or not.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Within the gurdwara, the Guru ka Langar (Guru's community kitchen) serves purely lacto-vegetarian food because the Langar is open to all.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Since people of many faiths have varying dietary taboos, and since Sikhs accept these restrictions and accommodate people regardless of their faith or culture, the Sikh Gurus adopt vegetarian food for Langar.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Meat was included in langar at the time of Guru Angad, but was discontinued to accommodate Vaishnavites.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Sikhism argues that the soul can possibly undergo millions of transformations as various forms of life before ultimately becoming human.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] These life forms could be a mineral, vegetation, or an animal.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Sikhism does not see a difference between these types of existence, however the human has a privileged position compared to other life forms.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] In terms of the Sikh view of karma, human life is seen as being most precious, and animal, vegetable, and mineral all viewed as being equally below human life.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Therefore, Sikhs view eating an animal is the same as eating a plant or mineral.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] According to Surjit Singh Gandhi, the *Guru Granth Sahib* on page 472 and Guru Nanak in early 16th century said that "avoidance of flesh as food was impractical and impossible so long as they used water, since water was the source of all life and the first life principle".
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Guru Nanak states that all living beings are connected.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Even meat comes from the consumption of vegetables, and all forms of life are based on water.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] The Akal Takht (Central Body for Sikh Temporal Affairs) represents the final authority on controversial issues concerning the Sikh Panth (community or collective).
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Some religious sects of Sikhism—Damdami Taksal, Akhand Kirtani Jatha, Namdharis, Guru Nanak Nishkam Sewak Jatha and the 3HO—believe that the Sikh diet should be meat-free.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] The reason for the disagreement with this ruling is that these sects had many Vaishnav converts to Sikhism who were staunchly vegetarian.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] The Akhand Kirtani Jatha dispute the meaning of the word "kutha", claiming it means all meat.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] However, in mainstream Sikhism this word has been accepted to mean that which has been prepared according to Muslim rituals.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] According to the Sikh code of conduct or Rehat Maryada, Sikhs are free to choose whether or not to include meat in their diet.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] The Sikh *Rehat Maryada* states that Sikhs cannot consume meat that is Halal (Muslim), or Kosher (Jewish).
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Singh states that throughout Sikh history, there have been many subsects of Sikhism that have espoused vegetarianism.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] However, this was rejected by the Sikh Gurus.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Sikhs consider that vegetarianism and meat-eating are unimportant in the realm of Sikh spirituality.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Surinder Singh Kohli links vegetarianism to Vashnavite behaviour.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Gopal Singh, commenting on meat being served in the langar during the time of Guru Angad Gyani Sher Singh—who was the head priest at the Darbar Sahib—notes that ahimsa does not fit in with Sikh doctrine.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Owen Cole and Piara Singh Sambhi comment that if the Sikh Gurus had made an issue on vegetarianism, it would have distracted from the main emphasis of Sikh spirituality.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Singha and Satwant Kaur comment on how ritually-slaughtered meat is considered a sin for initiated Sikhs.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Sidhu also notes that ritually-slaughtered meat is taboo for a Sikh.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Gurbakhsh Singh comments on how non-Kutha meat is acceptable for the Sikhs.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Surinder Singh Kohli comments on the "fools wrangle over flesh" quotation from the Guru Granth Sahib by noting how Guru Nanak mocked hypocritical vegetarian priests.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Gobind Singh Mansukhani states how vegetarianism and meat-eating has been left to the individual Sikh.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Devinder Singh Chahal comments on the difficulties of distinguishing between plant and animal in Sikh philosophy.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Singha comments in his book how the Sikh Gurus ate meat.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Khushwant Singh also notes that most Sikhs are meat-eaters and decry vegetarians as *daal khorey* (lentil-eaters).
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] In early 1987 *Kharkus* issued a moral code banning the sale and consumption of meat.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] The ban led to much of Punjab being without meat.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Those who continued to sell or eat meat risked death and commonly would have their businesses destroyed and be killed.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] One survey found that there were no meat or tobacco shops between Amritsar and Phagwara.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] In the peak of the militancy most of Punjab was meatless.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Famous restaurants that served meat had removed it from their menu and denied ever serving it.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Kharkus justified the ban by saying, "No avatars, Hindu or Sikh, ever did these things.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] According to *Dabistan-e-Mazhib* (a contemporary Persian chronology of the Sikh Gurus), Guru Nanak did not eat meat, and Guru Arjan thought that meat eating was not in accordance with Nanak's wishes.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Singh's research that states that Guru Nanak ate meat on the way to Kurukshetra.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] According to Persian records, Guru Hargobind (the 6th Guru) ate meat and hunted, and his practice was adopted by most Sikhs.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Sikhs also generally avoid eating beef because the cow, the buffalo and the ox are an integral part of rural Sikh livelihoods.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Similarly, Sikhs may avoid eating beef in the company of Hindus and avoid eating pork in the company of Muslims out of respect for their shared values.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] However, there is no religious prohibition about eating beef and pork.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Some Sikh groups like Akhand Kirtani Jatha keep Sarbloh Bibek.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Sikhs who follow this practice eat from iron bowls and iron plates only.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Another key aspect to maintaining Sarbloh Bibek is that Sikhs must only eat food prepared by other Amritdhari (baptized) Sikhs.
[src:diet-in-sikhism/diet-in-sikhism] Amritdhari Sikhs are also not to eat Jootha food (previously eaten food) from non-Amritdharis.
